               <note>
                  <ab type="description">The town of Gondar is located in today's <placeName
                        ref="LOC6544NorthGondar">North Gondar</placeName> Zone (historically
                        <placeName ref="LOC1713Bagemd">Bagemdǝr</placeName> province) in the
                        <placeName ref="LOC1426Amhara">ʾAmhāra</placeName> Regional State. It
                     evolved from an obscure <date>17th century</date> market town into the
                     flourishing capital of the Ethiopian monarchy, passed through an era of decline
                     and destruction and underwent a slow renaissance in the mid-<date>20th
                        century</date>. It is today one of the largest cities in <placeName
                        ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName>. Gondar started to flourish after
                     ʾaṣe <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> chose Gondar as his
                     camp to control the collection of customs on the <placeName ref="LOC5339RedSea"
                        >Red Sea</placeName> - <placeName ref="LOC5888Tana"> Ṭānā</placeName> -
                        <placeName ref="LOC2966Ennary">ʾƎnnāryā</placeName> trade routes. By the
                     late <date>17th century</date>, Gondar had become a permanent and sizeable
                     settlement where Ethiopians' rulers resided when not campaigning and where the
                     highest commerical, political and religious classes gathered around the
                     throne.</ab>
               </note>
            </place>
